observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the City Mayor instruct the City Accountant and the General Services Officer (GSO) to take the following specific actions or measures to address the discrepancy of P444,632,007.23 between the accounting records and inventory report, to wit:
a. The Accounting Office update and maintain the PPE Ledger Cards indicating therein the details of every property acquired by the City, such as the acquisition, description, custody, estimated useful life, depreciation, impairment loss, disposal and other information about the asset;
b. The GSO determine the composition of Land Improvements reported in lump-sum, report the results of inventory for buildings, structures and public infrastructures in the prescribed RPCPPE and to group the physically counted PPE according to type or category of assets;
c. The GSO update and maintain the Property Cards according to account classification; and
d. The Accounting and GSO reconcile their respective PPE records on a regular basis.

We reiterated our recommendations that the City Mayor direct:
a. the Inventory Committee to complete the inventory count of all properties owned by the City to prove its existence and to submit the required report thereon to the Auditor;
b. the City Accountant to provide details in the PPE Ledger Cards being maintained by their Office to provide adequate information of the PPE; Make sure that PPELC and Real Property Cards per category of PPE are properly maintained and up-dated;
c. the General Services Officer to make certain that Property Cards are properly maintained, complete and updated to facilitate the physical count of property and equipment;
d. the City Accountant and the GSO to continue their efforts to reconcile and determine the nature of the discrepancies noted in the PPE accounts and make the necessary adjustments/ corrections, whenever applicable; and
e. the City GSO to prepare the updated IIRUP, to account for all unserviceable and obsolete items previously taken up in the books so as they may be properly disposed of and dropped from the PPE accounts. Consequently, the disposal shall be made in accordance with COA Circular No. 89-296.

We reiterated our recommendation that the City Mayor direct the General Services Office to ensure adequate control over the motor vehicles of the City by performing the following control measures:
 reconcile the Inventory Report of Transportation Equipment with Accounting records;
 immediately register in the name of the City the motor vehicles still registered in the name of the previous owner;
 make follow-up from the LTO regarding the motor vehicles with no plate numbers;
 exert effort to retrieve documents for those motor vehicles with no records on file in the General Services Office;
 observe annual registration of all vehicles; and
 prepare the required Inventory and Inspection of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for all motor vehicles found unserviceable to facilitate the disposal of the same.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct the General Services Office to ensure adequate control over the motor vehicles of the City by performing the following control measures:
Reconcile the Inventory Report of Transportation Equipment with Accounting records;
Immediately register to the name of the City the motor vehicles still registered in the name of the previous owner;
Make follow-up with the LTO regarding the car plates of motor vehicles with no plate numbers yet;
Exert effort to retrieve documents for those motor vehicles with no records on file in the General Services Office;
Observe annual registration of all motor vehicles;
Investigate the whereabouts of those motor vehicles not presented during the physical inventory-taking;
Prepare the required Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for all motor vehicles found unserviceable to facilitate the disposal of the same;
Renew and update Acknowledgement Receipts for Equipment (ARE) issued for motor vehicles for proper control and accountability; and
Ensure proper maintenance of transportation equipment for them to reach the maximum useful life.
